transcript.text: Hello, welcome back to the On Print Shop Designer Studio tutorial series.
In today's video we will learn how to create a mass image in Adobe Illustrator tool.
To give you a brief, a mass image helps in applying A shaping effect on the images used while designing the product.
So how you can create it on your own?
The answer is using image tools.
In this video we will show you the steps to create mass images from the Illustrator tool.
O let's get started.
First of all, open the illustrator tool and then open a new file.
You can select any size as per your preference.
We have taken a file with 512 Ixels width and height which is a square shape file.
You need to set the color mode as RGB.
Select screen 72 PPI and finally click on the OK button.
So your new document as per specifications will appear with the artboard.
Now create 1 shape like we are creating a square here and then fill this with Gray color in the shape.
You can define the size of the shape from the above bar.
We are keeping the size the same as the document, 512 pixels.
Now align the object to the center of the artboard by using alignment tools from the top side of control panel.
Next, you need to create a circle by using an ellipse tool and align it to the center.
Here we are creating a rounded shape in the middle to create a mass image.
Then make sure that this layer is on the top of the square.
Now select both the square and round shapes and then click on the Pathfinder icon from the right sidebar and then from the options, click on the Minus front option.
So as you can see the center part which is a circle shape is now transparent.
Just align this to the center and fill it with white color.
Now navigate to the File menu, select Export and export this file as a PNG.
In the PNG options screen, select 72 PPI as the resolution and then click on OK.
This is how you can create a mass image in Adobe Illustrator.
Similarly, you can create mass images for different shapes.
For example, if you want to create a round border kind of mass image.
In that case you first need to make a circle, align it with the artboard and then create a copy by pressing Control C and then Control F which will create an exact copy upon the same circle.
Now resize 1 circle to make it a little bit smaller than the other one.
Now we are repeating the same process by selecting both circles, selecting the Pathfinder and clicking on the minus front option.
Now fill the Gray portion with the white color and then export the file in PNG format.
In the same way, you can create a square into a square or a square into a circle shape.
At the end, you need to upload these masks in the Onprint Shop admin panel to be displayed in the Designer Studio for personalization.
Hope you enjoyed the video.
If you have any questions, our support executives are here to help.
Just reach out through live chat on onprintshop.com.
Thanks for tuning in.
